Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons.
Long before Turkey thought of joining the European Union, European powers were eager to enter its hinterland.
On the east side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps from Asia, is one of the finest relics of its fallen imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed in a neo-renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that's what the guides tell us.
The monument is placed on horseback at the bottom of the platforms, equipped with observation towers at each of its corners, like some German provincial town halls.
The stones are dirty.
The whole building is in ruins.
But once inside the vaulted ticket office, we have no doubt about the size of the company, which represents a passage to the west.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by a German association, Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a delay in the game of imperialism, wanted to realize its medieval ambitions of domination thanks to this railway that arrives in Damascus, Baghdad as well as the land more known as Saudi Arabia.
But German imperialist ambitions collapsed during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The relative isolation of its surrounding area, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is over.
. The British and the forces of the empire advanced beyond Egypt and pushed the Turkish and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there was also bad news for Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded destroying its subtle roof.
Turkish sources state that this is sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly fallen into ruin, swallowed up in the meanderings of history.
But today, the rail crossing to Anatolia and all the eastern points, at least symbolically, serves to underline the widening of Turkey's diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of its surrounding area, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War
