The Turkish government has remarkable relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian fractions of Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To judge the parameters of this new foreign policy, I embarked on a car-bed in the direction of the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit MP Turkish AKP Suât Kiniklioglu, one of the experts in foreign policy.
The next morning, after a journey of 10 and a half hours, shaken on noisy tracks whose cadence reminded the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived, in the Turkish capital- presented as a new city of a new secular state, turning my back on its German past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamist roots is an example of a change in the Turkish consensus.
He suspected the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi accompanied me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra modern structure, specifically built of stones and steel, in a developing area, surrounded by half-built shopping centres and numerous pastries in which middle managers in suit-travate- men and women- meet for morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a middle-right politician from any other party in Europe.
Costume, tie and he even has a Black Berry.
"the aim of this foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey now into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Now she has to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't the case for both.
She had to do both.
"but, now, at some point, "I asked if" Turkey should not choose?".
"Turkey" he said "does not want to have to choose between the two."
