The 'Bee Car' which avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan drew on nature, especially bees, this time.
The Japanese company created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Centre have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Centre for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan security shield.
This robot will allow the brand's vehicles to prevent collisions.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that looks much like the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the eyes composed of the bee, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles over a distance of two metres and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"At the moment when it detects an obstacle, the small robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by forking its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape manoeuvre is totally instinctive.
If that were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Transportation Laboratory and senior engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted upwards or downwards, nor diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a function of rotation, but also of acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
" Each second this device must only process information and act according to that data.
It does not need to keep the information or intuitive logics of prior maneuvers, that is why it can operate continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes."
This is the first because of the development of new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced into standard cars in ten years after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
