"This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to banking holding status," said John Mack, general manager of the American group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which is intended to allow him to diversify his activities but to pass it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street's biggest names to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the agreement has been amended in the last few days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago," explained Tokyo Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, "we thought the participation would be entirely composed of ordinary shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimize risks and cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert in one year half of its preferential shares into common shares if the latter exchange more than 50% above the conversion price, that is to say about 47 dollars, for a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital provided by MUFG will enable him to seize investment opportunities, strengthen his balance sheet and increase his liquidity.
However, a spokesperson for the group refused to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG's investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to have a Tier One solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said he had "clearly" lightened his balance sheet since the end of August.
