Rafael Correa to Quito this Monday.
Refound the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, it was the third that put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" received 28%, 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% were white.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out outside the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organisation had announced a large victory of the "yes", between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft Constitution from Sunday to Monday.
The "Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly," he said, congratulating the Equatorians at the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometres south-west of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place calmly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the President.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the State over the economy, reserving to it the "planning of the development" of a country living essentially from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and foreign currencies sent by its emigrants.
Ported by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the Head of State, who will be able to serve up to two consecutive terms of four years and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and will be seeking a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services which the President has begun to establish in that country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian commando attacked the abductors of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back this Monday afternoon safe and sound in the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at about 3.30 p.m. on a special plane at the military base in al-Maza, next to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to Maadi Hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers," said Egyptian tourism minister Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
Captured on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been balked from one cache to the other by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous agency, organiser of the safari.
An Egyptian security official reported that 30 Special Forces personnel, on board two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunshots occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others running away," said the official who demanded anonymity.
He indicated that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "flash" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men in the secret services, the special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The previous day, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on which the kidnappers were carrying during a patrol, killing in six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture is in the headlines and is taking place in this election campaign.
Good.
But one sector of our cultural life is still forgotten.
Who will rise to denounce the amount of misery that is being given to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historic sites that are starving?
Which politician dares to remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government devotes three and a half million euros to the restoration of the only Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
Among our American neighbours, it is written in their country's Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of the Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, elected officials and all government departments, in concert.
In Quebec, at the Fédération des sociétés d'histoire du Québec, at least 40,000 volunteers in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with searching history, preserving with three under piles of private archives and preserving archaeological remains.
They are often the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when promoters and decision makers launch their bulldozers against our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When is a forum for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Holland bank, as the first European bank in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalising it. The three countries bear a sum of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also having interest in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, in this case, also calling on the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been growing for more than a year is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back almost half (49%) of the bank's capital in each of the countries.
The bank will, without a doubt, sell part of its holdings, among which, in the first place, the essentially insurance activities it acquired last year from the Dutch body ABN Amro.
Last week, the Fortis shares began a staggering fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too large to let it go to bankruptcy.
On Friday alone, the company's shares dropped by 12 percent, to its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two thirds of their value.
Taking into account the present value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around EUR 14 billion, which, according to the company's management, is not realistic.
The company's management is aware of the uncertainty of the overseas Atlantic, in connection with the adoption of the US rescue plan of $700 billion, to be at the origin of the fall of the Fortis shares.
On Monday, there has already been a slight increase in the number of papers.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new general manager.
The financial agency was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the substance.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's client circle and no agency was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also bought leasing companies.
A fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate on the basis of information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes that link the use of prescription information in all cases to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it's like entrusting its henhouse to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage drug prescriptions, at the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the capital insured in case of damage depend on the health condition of the client who presents himself, and if they consider that the risk is too great, they do not even guarantee it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they did not sign an insurance contract with them until they became aware of the results.
For the last ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies, data concerning the person's drug purchases within the last eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person is suffering from and what is his state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts it in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is no longer much to do to the insurer other than paperwork. However, tiny problems may still appear.
Disadvantages of this program include the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of the data, and they must ask the patient for authorisation before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their failure in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory analyses and linking them with data on drug use. In this way, they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and control over use is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the expansion of the control circle of authorities concerning data supply companies is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent, since if he or she refuses, the insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus and ultimately, hens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
Marseille's global menu
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global, problems.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit, which will focus on cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is a major emerging democratic power that should be given a broader voice in international affairs, but member countries have not yet managed to agree on their support in New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not, moreover, dwell too much on this issue yesterday at the 9th summit held in Marseilles.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, like the current President of the Union, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy Javier Solana, welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would double trade, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Taking into account that, between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overambitious goal.
In this sense, they have harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil flights from a legal point of view. In this way, air exchanges can also grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's leading trading partner, on the one hand, and New Delhi, on the other, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan has been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on this subject has been mentioned.
The completion of the Doha trade round has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20 per cent until 2020.
India also agreed on this, as well as with the fact that a global market would have to be reached at next year's climate conference, and that greenhouse gas emissions would have to be reduced by 50 per cent until 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Head of State is now travelling to the French capital, where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to news agency information, the agreement would cover 15 years.
