Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire missing a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying on the Nevada Desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3000 metres, in the area of the Sierra Nevada of Mammanth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County's sheriff, John Anderson, avoided the doubts that remained: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one Steve Fosset was travelling on the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff therefore specified that no human remains were found either on the aircraft or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (Ntsb) reported that a few hours after the wreckage was identified by a team of investigators at the scene, it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on 3 September 2007, when Fosset decave from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal belongings were found by a couple around their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents bearing the name Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's research was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had gained a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
On the sixth attempt, he had become in 2002, the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had flown around the world without a stopover.
Of all these records, also that of flying at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
